what is gravity: gravity is the force that attracts objects toward the center of the earth
or toward any other physical body having mass.
who is isaac newton: isaac newton was an english mathematician
and astronomer who is widely recognized as one of the most influential scientists of all time. he formulated the laws of motion and universal gravitation.
what is photosynthesis: photosynthesis is the process by which green plants and some other organisms use sunlight to synthesize foods with the help of chlorophyll
what is dna: dna (deoxyribonucleic acid) is a molecule that carries the genetic instructions used in the growth
and reproduction of all known living organisms.
what is the speed of light: the speed of light in a vacuum is approximately 299
282 miles per second). it is a fundamental constant of nature.
who invented the telephone: alexander graham bell is credited with inventing the telephone in 1876.
what is the capital of france: the capital of france is paris
known as the city of light.
what is the largest ocean: the largest ocean on earth is the pacific ocean
what are the seven wonders of the world: the seven wonders of the ancient world were a list of remarkable constructions known to ancient greek travelers. they include the great pyramid of giza
the statue of zeus at olympia
the temple of artemis at ephesus
what is global warming: global warming refers to the long-term increase in earth's average surface temperature due to human activities
primarily the burning of fossil fuels which releases greenhouse gases into the atmosphere.
who painted the mona lisa: the mona lisa was painted by leonardo da vinci
and is considered one of the most famous paintings in the world.
what is the function of the heart: the heart is a muscular organ that pumps blood throughout the body via the circulatory system
supplying oxygen and nutrients to the tissues and removing carbon dioxide and other waste products.
what is the milky way: the milky way is the galaxy that contains our solar system. it is a barred spiral galaxy with a diameter of about 100
000 light-years and contains billions of stars
what is the periodic table: the periodic table is a tabular arrangement of chemical elements organized by their atomic number
and recurring chemical properties. it is widely used in chemistry and other sciences.
who wrote romeo and juliet: romeo and juliet is a tragedy written by william shakespeare
believed to have been written between 1591 and 1595.
what is the great wall of china: the great wall of china is a series of fortifications made of stone
built along the northern borders of china to protect against invasions.
what is the human digestive system: the human digestive system is a series of organs that work together to convert food into energy and essential nutrients. it includes the mouth
who discovered penicillin: was discovered by sir alexander fleming
what is the greenhouse effect: the greenhouse effect is the process by which radiation from a planet's atmosphere warms the planet's surface to a temperature above what it would be without its atmosphere. it is crucial for sustaining life on earth.
who painted the starry night: the starry night is a famous painting by vincent van gogh
what is the function of the lungs: the lungs are organs of the respiratory system that allow us to breathe. they exchange oxygen and carbon dioxide between the air we breathe and the blood.
who wrote the declaration of independenc: the declaration of independence was primarily written by thomas jefferson
one of the founding fathers of the united states
what is the purpose of the united nation: the united nations (un) is an international organization founded in 1945 after world war ii to promote international cooperation
and foster sustainable development and human rights.
who discovered america: an italian explorer sponsored by spain
is traditionally credited with discovering the americas in 1492.
what are renewable energy sources: renewable energy sources are energy sources that are naturally replenished on a human timescale
who is marie curie: marie curie was a polish-born physicist and chemist who conducted pioneering research on radioactivity. she was the first woman to win a nobel prize and remains the only person to win nobel prizes in two different scientific fields.
what is the function of the kidneys: the kidneys are vital organs of the urinary system that filter blood
and maintain fluid balance in the body.
who was leonardo da vinci: leonardo da vinci was an italian polymath of the renaissance whose areas of interest included invention
and cartography. he is widely considered one of the greatest painters of all time and a universal genius.
what is the theory of evolution: the theory of evolution is a scientific theory that explains how species change over time through natural selection
and mutation. it was proposed by charles darwin in his book "on the origin of species" in 1859.
what are the parts of the human eye: the human eye consists of several parts including the cornea
and optic nerve. each part plays a crucial role in the visual process.
what are the main parts of the brain: the human brain has several main parts including the cerebrum
and brainstem. the cerebrum controls voluntary actions and cognitive functions
while the cerebellum coordinates motor movements and balance.
what are the bones in the human body: the human body has 206 bones that form the skeletal system. major bones include the skull
what are the functions of the heart: the heart is a muscular organ that pumps blood throughout the body. its main functions include delivering oxygen and nutrients to tissues
what are the parts of the digestive syst: the human digestive system consists of the mouth
and pancreas. these organs work together to digest food
what are the major muscles in the human: major muscles in the human body include the biceps
and pectoral muscles. these muscles enable movement
what are the functions of the lungs: the lungs are vital organs of the respiratory system that facilitate the exchange of oxygen and carbon dioxide between the air and blood. they also help maintain acid-base balance in the body.
what are the parts of the ear: the human ear consists of three main parts: the outer ear (including the pinna and ear canal)
the middle ear (including the eardrum and ossicles)
and the inner ear (including the cochlea and semicircular canals). these parts work together to facilitate hearing and balance.
what are the functions of the kidneys: the kidneys are vital organs of the urinary system that filter blood
and maintain fluid balance in the body.
what are the parts of the respiratory sy: the human respiratory system consists of the nose
and lungs. these organs work together to facilitate the exchange of gases (oxygen and carbon dioxide) between the body and the environment.
